WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Next up, we have Max Kuhn.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:16.920
Hi, thanks for coming.

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:24.420
So probably maybe to nobody's surprise, I'm going to talk about model tuning again.

00:00:24.420 --> 00:00:30.320
So my job within the Tidyverse group is to work on kind of all types of modeling and

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:33.060
how we can do that in a more tidy way.

00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:51.860
The place to start for us, normally would be with more predictive models, but tidy models

00:00:51.860 --> 00:00:54.900
infrastructure is not really constrained to do just that.

00:00:54.900 --> 00:00:57.820
We want to work on inferential models and descriptive models and all sorts of other

00:00:57.820 --> 00:00:59.259
things.

00:00:59.259 --> 00:01:02.180
Some of these models need what we call parameter tuning, and that's what I'm going to talk

00:01:02.180 --> 00:01:06.860
about today in this new package we have called Tune.

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:11.059
So most of our Tidy models packages, we tend, in the Tidyverse, we don't tend to write like

00:01:11.059 --> 00:01:14.580
one huge package that does all the things in it.

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:17.639
So we tend to write packages that are interconnected with each other.

00:01:17.639 --> 00:01:21.059
And so in doing so, before I can show you what Tune does, I have to show you what a

00:01:21.059 --> 00:01:29.339
few other packages inside Tidy models and how they work and how they feed into Tune.

00:01:29.339 --> 00:01:36.980
So if you've never seen Tidy models before, we're going to start with what I like to call

00:01:36.980 --> 00:01:40.500
the new Iris data, which is the Ames housing data.

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:44.099
It's basically we have sale prices on houses in Ames, Iowa.

00:01:44.099 --> 00:01:45.099
That's what's shown here.

00:01:45.099 --> 00:01:49.379
We have data in different neighborhoods, and then we have all these features of houses

00:01:49.379 --> 00:01:53.580
like their general living area, what type of building it is, and that kind of thing.

00:01:53.580 --> 00:01:57.860
So the goal here would be to predict what the sale price is of a house based on the

00:01:57.860 --> 00:02:06.180
characteristics of its data set, like the other aspects of the house.

00:02:06.180 --> 00:02:09.100
So let's say we were going to preprocess our data using recipes.

00:02:09.100 --> 00:02:12.500
So recipes, if you've never seen it, is a package that is really good at doing feature

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:16.380
engineering and preprocessing every data before you put it in the model.

00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:21.460
It follows this analogy of baking a cake or making something to eat.

00:02:21.460 --> 00:02:25.419
So in a recipe, the first thing you start with when you look at a recipe is here are

00:02:25.419 --> 00:02:27.440
the ingredients into the recipe.

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:33.580
So if we load the Tidy models package, that loads most of our individual packages.

00:02:33.580 --> 00:02:34.580
So it's like a meta package.

00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:37.779
Then we can load the Ames housing data and create the data.

00:02:37.779 --> 00:02:42.979
So the initial recipe here, all it really does is says the ingredients into our recipe

00:02:42.979 --> 00:02:45.339
is we have a column called sale price.

00:02:45.339 --> 00:02:46.339
That's our outcome.

00:02:46.339 --> 00:02:50.899
And then I just picked a couple of predictors here to look at that are in this data set.

00:02:50.899 --> 00:02:53.419
And the recipe doesn't really do anything at this point.

00:02:53.419 --> 00:02:58.720
It's just beginning to say here's a list of the specification of things we want to do.

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:02.460
And the way recipes works is it's kind of like dplyr or ggplot where you can just keep

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:06.419
layering in things that you want to do to the data in the order in which you want to

00:03:06.419 --> 00:03:07.419
do them.

00:03:07.419 --> 00:03:10.979
So sale price is very much right skewed along with a couple other variables.

00:03:10.979 --> 00:03:14.339
So you can add a step to your recipe that says log in the data.

00:03:14.339 --> 00:03:18.660
You can use basic dplyr selectors, including like ends with and things like that.

00:03:18.660 --> 00:03:22.779
And you can tell it what base to use.

00:03:22.779 --> 00:03:26.139
Neighborhood that I highlighted in that map has some interesting characteristics where

00:03:26.139 --> 00:03:31.100
there are a few neighborhoods with only a handful of observations in the data set.

00:03:31.100 --> 00:03:35.460
So what happens sometimes is when you have a variable that is very unbalanced in its

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:39.660
frequency, if you like resample the data or so want to make dummy variables, it's very

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:43.539
often you get some columns that have like all zeros in the dummy variable column.

00:03:43.539 --> 00:03:47.259
So we have a step called step other that what it can do is based on a frequency cut

00:03:47.259 --> 00:03:52.860
off that you use, for example, the one here, you can say anything that has less than 5%

00:03:52.860 --> 00:03:54.539
of the training set in this neighborhood.

00:03:54.539 --> 00:03:59.820
Let's dump that into another category called other and then redefine our factor levels

00:03:59.820 --> 00:04:03.539
for that variable to have other in it instead of the original levels.

00:04:03.539 --> 00:04:04.539
So that's something you can do.

00:04:04.539 --> 00:04:06.660
You can make dummy variables.

00:04:06.660 --> 00:04:10.259
You see there's like a recipe selector here that will select all the character or all

00:04:10.259 --> 00:04:12.500
the factor variables.

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:15.460
And then based on that, you can add a few more things.

00:04:15.460 --> 00:04:18.779
We know from this data set that there's a linear effect between the general living area

00:04:18.779 --> 00:04:22.859
of a house and its sale price, both on a log scale, but we've noticed over time that different

00:04:22.859 --> 00:04:24.940
building types have different slopes.

00:04:24.940 --> 00:04:25.940
So that's an interaction effect.

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:28.619
So you can specify interactions.

00:04:28.619 --> 00:04:30.540
We can also include splines.

00:04:30.540 --> 00:04:36.859
So if you do a plot of sale price versus longitude or latitude, you see there's really wavy type

00:04:36.859 --> 00:04:38.660
relationships between these two variables.

00:04:39.540 --> 00:04:44.420
Instead of modeling these predictors in a linear way, you could use a natural spline,

00:04:44.420 --> 00:04:50.179
so step NS, to replace the original, let's say, latitude predictor with a basis expansion,

00:04:50.179 --> 00:04:53.859
like basically a couple of nonlinear terms that represent that data.

00:04:53.859 --> 00:04:58.779
And that allows that variable to be predicted or modeled in a nonlinear way.

00:04:58.779 --> 00:05:02.380
So if you ever use GM smooth, chances are, depending on the size of your data, you've

00:05:02.380 --> 00:05:06.420
used a spline to figure out what that nonlinear relationship is.

00:05:06.459 --> 00:05:10.540
So what you would do with this recipe is you would apply these steps in a separate function

00:05:10.540 --> 00:05:11.540
call.

00:05:11.540 --> 00:05:12.540
You would apply these steps to your training set.

00:05:12.540 --> 00:05:15.859
It would do all these operations in sequence, and that would give you like a ready-made

00:05:15.859 --> 00:05:18.859
data set that you could then put into a model.

00:05:18.859 --> 00:05:23.459
So in terms of modeling, oh, and one other thing here is I chose, just based on looking

00:05:23.459 --> 00:05:27.399
the data, to use five degrees of freedom for the spline.

00:05:27.399 --> 00:05:31.459
So lower degrees of freedom means it's less smooth, like linear, and higher degrees of

00:05:31.459 --> 00:05:34.260
freedom allow it to be more potentially smooth.

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:38.540
All right, so you might think about using the parsing package to do modeling.

00:05:38.540 --> 00:05:43.299
And if you've never seen that before, it's very similar recipes in that you make a specification

00:05:43.299 --> 00:05:45.540
of what you want to do before you actually do it.

00:05:45.540 --> 00:05:49.500
So let's say we just want to fit some type of linear regression model, like numeric outcome,

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:52.859
we know we're going to have slopes and intercepts, that's like the structure of our model.

00:05:52.859 --> 00:05:56.119
So in parsing, we have all these functions that delineate, like you want to do this type

00:05:56.119 --> 00:06:01.339
of structure, like k-nearest neighbors, or linear regression, or like a neural network.

00:06:01.339 --> 00:06:05.260
So first you state what type of model you want to have, which is not really terribly

00:06:05.260 --> 00:06:07.779
descriptive as you can see when we print it out.

00:06:07.779 --> 00:06:09.420
And then you'd state the engine.

00:06:09.420 --> 00:06:12.459
So the engine is basically what implementation do you want to use.

00:06:12.459 --> 00:06:16.859
So you might use an implementation that does Bayesian analysis to estimate your parameters,

00:06:16.859 --> 00:06:18.980
or like a robust regression and so on.

00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:19.980
So you have a lot of options.

00:06:19.980 --> 00:06:23.980
I'm going to choose Glimnit here, which is like a regularized regression model.

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:28.220
But you could have used LM, or Stan, or Kieris, or all the things that we have implemented.

00:06:28.220 --> 00:06:31.019
And so now you've been a little more specific, saying we want to fit this structure of this

00:06:31.700 --> 00:06:35.420
model, but use this estimation to estimate parameters.

00:06:35.420 --> 00:06:38.179
And so I mentioned Glimnit does regularized regression.

00:06:38.179 --> 00:06:41.500
So there are also some other parameters that we probably should specify for Glimnit.

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:46.140
For example, the amount of regularization in this value called penalty, this is a fairly

00:06:46.140 --> 00:06:48.339
high amount of regularization.

00:06:48.339 --> 00:06:52.220
And then what Glimnit can do is it could fit two different types of regularization.

00:06:52.220 --> 00:06:56.660
It could fit the lasso model, which is like L1 regularization, or it could do ridge regression,

00:06:56.660 --> 00:06:58.059
which is like L2 regularization.

00:06:58.500 --> 00:07:01.500
And the cool thing about it is you can choose a mixture of these things.

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:04.779
So if you're not sure whether you should be doing the lasso or ridge regression, you could

00:07:04.779 --> 00:07:08.820
try a mixture of the two to see if that works better for you than just purely one or the

00:07:08.820 --> 00:07:09.820
other.

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:14.980
So in this call, I picked a fairly high amount of regularization and about a 50-50 mixture

00:07:14.980 --> 00:07:18.500
of lasso and ridge regression.

00:07:18.500 --> 00:07:21.500
And you can see when I print it out, it's there.

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:22.500
But how do I know?

00:07:22.500 --> 00:07:23.579
I have all these special numbers, right?

00:07:23.579 --> 00:07:27.179
Like five degrees of freedom, a penalty value of 0.1, and so on.

00:07:27.299 --> 00:07:30.500
So you might say, oh, you must have done a lot of analysis for this.

00:07:30.500 --> 00:07:33.959
But basically, I can't look at those numbers and say that's a great model.

00:07:33.959 --> 00:07:36.459
So the thing about this is we need to tune these values.

00:07:36.459 --> 00:07:40.339
If you want to optimize our model performance, and we don't know what these values are, and

00:07:40.339 --> 00:07:45.260
there's no analytical function that says plug your x's and y's in, and therefore, it spits

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:46.859
out a value of whatever for penalty.

00:07:46.859 --> 00:07:51.459
So we have to do something to find reasonable values of these parameters when we can't directly

00:07:51.459 --> 00:07:52.459
estimate them.

00:07:52.459 --> 00:07:53.459
And that's called model tuning.

00:07:53.459 --> 00:07:56.739
I'm going to show you the tune package in just a second.

00:07:56.739 --> 00:07:59.459
Basically, I have at least two ways of doing that model tuning.

00:07:59.459 --> 00:08:03.179
And what we're going to do is we're going to figure out ways of tagging which parameters

00:08:03.179 --> 00:08:04.179
do I want to optimize.

00:08:04.179 --> 00:08:07.540
So let's say I only want to optimize mixture and keep everything else the same.

00:08:07.540 --> 00:08:11.579
So how would we tell the tune package which actual parameters that we should optimize?

00:08:11.579 --> 00:08:14.820
So we're going to do that in a second.

00:08:14.820 --> 00:08:16.540
So I've been at RStudio for three years.

00:08:16.540 --> 00:08:21.299
I've been thinking about this particular problem for 20 years.

00:08:21.299 --> 00:08:25.380
And so when I started working on parsnip and recipes, I've been putting a lot of thought

00:08:25.380 --> 00:08:29.019
about, okay, how is this going to feed into the packages like tune that come later in

00:08:29.019 --> 00:08:30.859
the pipe?

00:08:30.859 --> 00:08:35.460
And so I was trying to figure out a way to summarize that, that this audience would understand

00:08:35.460 --> 00:08:39.400
maybe, or at least some percentage of this audience would get, and this is what I came

00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:42.299
up with.

00:08:42.299 --> 00:08:46.020
So if you've ever listened to not-so-standard deviations, you'll know that Hillary, if you're

00:08:46.020 --> 00:08:48.659
here, sorry.

00:08:48.659 --> 00:08:53.059
But a lot of really intense conversations about coffee, and that's how I've been thinking

00:08:53.059 --> 00:08:56.059
about this particular package.

00:08:56.059 --> 00:08:59.900
So okay, so here's, let's say we load the tune package, but that'll be included in tiny

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:00.900
models.

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:03.940
These are just the recipe and model objects that I just showed you.

00:09:03.940 --> 00:09:07.500
And so what we want to do is we want to say, which of these parameters do you want to optimize

00:09:07.500 --> 00:09:10.179
in some way to find good performance measures?

00:09:10.179 --> 00:09:14.020
So what we're going to do is we're going to substitute these actual values in with a function

00:09:14.020 --> 00:09:15.659
call called tune.

00:09:15.659 --> 00:09:18.260
And this function call doesn't actually do anything.

00:09:18.260 --> 00:09:22.619
It just returns an expression that says tune.

00:09:22.619 --> 00:09:27.979
Maybe not as happy as I just did, but the point is, if you've ever used recipes or parsenip,

00:09:27.979 --> 00:09:31.340
the thing is, when you create your recipe or you create your parsenip model object,

00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:34.260
it doesn't automatically just go ahead and fit those things.

00:09:34.260 --> 00:09:36.739
So we capture all these expressions and values.

00:09:36.739 --> 00:09:40.619
So we can add in a function value there, because we haven't actually evaluated any of these

00:09:40.619 --> 00:09:41.619
arguments.

00:09:41.619 --> 00:09:45.500
So if we wanted to say which variables we're going to tune, we can actually, instead of

00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:49.539
putting a five in here, put this value in, and we'll do it for this one and this one.

00:09:49.539 --> 00:09:53.380
So we can have, actually, other values that we keep constant if we like them, but then

00:09:53.380 --> 00:09:59.020
when we feed this into the machinery of tune, it would understand which ones we should look

00:09:59.020 --> 00:10:00.020
at.

00:10:00.020 --> 00:10:05.299
And we've interlaced everything between recipes and parsenip and this other package of dials

00:10:05.299 --> 00:10:07.820
where we've used a common nomenclature for everything.

00:10:07.820 --> 00:10:13.119
So as you'll see in a little bit, there's a lot of really good defaults of everything.

00:10:13.119 --> 00:10:17.140
So if you don't know what range of penalty you should use or what you should be doing,

00:10:17.140 --> 00:10:21.859
we have a lot of fairly safe choices that you can use to automate the selection of what

00:10:21.859 --> 00:10:24.460
grid you should use and what values and ranges.

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:27.859
So these things all sort of work together, and if you want to specify as much as possible,

00:10:27.859 --> 00:10:29.059
you can do that.

00:10:29.059 --> 00:10:32.260
But if you just want to let the machine figure it out, or if you feel like, oh, I don't know

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:38.140
what I should do, our reasonable defaults are there to sort of do that for you.

00:10:38.140 --> 00:10:44.380
So one thing about this is we're giving longitude and latitude the same amount of smoothness

00:10:44.380 --> 00:10:46.539
or wiggliness in the model.

00:10:46.539 --> 00:10:48.659
And we might want to separate those out.

00:10:48.659 --> 00:10:52.859
Maybe longitude wants a little bit of smoothing, and the other variable wants a lot of smoothing.

00:10:52.859 --> 00:10:57.419
So what we might do is we might say, well, let's create two different calls, and then

00:10:57.419 --> 00:11:02.380
we've given them separate identifiability.

00:11:02.380 --> 00:11:06.099
But the problem with this is when Tune parses this, it sees that there are two parameters

00:11:06.099 --> 00:11:10.020
called degrees of freedom that you're tuning, and it doesn't have a really good sense of

00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:12.580
like, well, how do I distinguish one from the other?

00:11:12.580 --> 00:11:16.219
So one thing you can do, whether you have this prop or not, is you can sort of annotate

00:11:16.219 --> 00:11:17.500
the names of these parameters.

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:20.820
You can, like, if you want to recognize them later and type something in that your boss

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:25.820
will recognize if you show them some plots, you can add some ID fields here.

00:11:25.820 --> 00:11:30.619
So the one argument to Tune is basically an optional character string that this is how

00:11:30.619 --> 00:11:36.780
that particular parameter will be identified in plots and things like that, and it also

00:11:36.780 --> 00:11:40.780
lets you differentiate what this degree of freedom parameter is from this one.

00:11:40.780 --> 00:11:44.539
And so sometimes you would need to do this, but other times you might just do it because

00:11:44.539 --> 00:11:48.299
you want to use a name that, like, makes a lot of sense for you.

00:11:48.299 --> 00:11:51.979
So now that we defined what we want to do, there's a couple different ways we could optimize

00:11:51.979 --> 00:11:52.979
these parameters.

00:11:52.979 --> 00:11:56.460
And the most, like, standard old-school way of doing it, which I think works really well,

00:11:56.460 --> 00:11:57.900
is use grid search.

00:11:57.900 --> 00:12:02.260
And in grid search, the ingredients to that is you need to have, like, some specification

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:05.219
of, like, what you want to do, so your model and your recipe.

00:12:05.219 --> 00:12:09.580
And then you also need to have, or at least we prescribe you to have, some specification

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:12.820
or some object that dictates how you want to resample the data.

00:12:12.820 --> 00:12:16.539
So what we don't want to do is we just don't want to take our data set, build a model with

00:12:16.539 --> 00:12:19.179
these parameters, and just re-predict the data set.

00:12:19.179 --> 00:12:22.780
So whether it's, like, a separate single validation set or whether you do bootstrapping or tenfold

00:12:22.780 --> 00:12:27.619
cross-validation, a sort of required ingredient that we don't really have a good default for

00:12:27.619 --> 00:12:31.299
deliberately is some resampling specification.

00:12:31.299 --> 00:12:38.340
Optionally, you can define a pre-existing grid of candidates that you are in particular

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:39.460
interested in investigating.

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:41.260
But if you don't, we'll make some for you.

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:45.260
And another thing we can do for you that you can specify is, you know, whether you want

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:50.340
to optimize, I don't know, median absolute error or root mean squared error.

00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:54.020
So we have defaults for these if you don't want to go there.

00:12:54.020 --> 00:12:57.659
So what we're going to do is we're just really going to specify these two things.

00:12:57.659 --> 00:12:59.619
For resampling, we're going to use the RSample package.

00:12:59.619 --> 00:13:04.059
There's enough data here where tenfold cross-validation will be fine.

00:13:04.059 --> 00:13:10.900
The defaults here give you tenfold, and that's in this object.

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:14.940
So our tuning parameters inside this function start with tune under bar.

00:13:14.940 --> 00:13:17.140
So tune grid does grid search.

00:13:17.140 --> 00:13:20.619
And then if you look at the arguments to that, here's our recipe and our model.

00:13:20.619 --> 00:13:25.539
Again, these are the versions of that that have the placeholder in there for tune.

00:13:25.539 --> 00:13:29.539
Here's the resampling object that we need to specify.

00:13:29.539 --> 00:13:33.700
And then I wouldn't have needed to do this, but I just said, you know, give me ten tuning

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:39.020
parameter values, like combinations of those four parameters to try based on what you know

00:13:39.140 --> 00:13:43.140
about these parameters and ranges that seem to be applicable.

00:13:43.140 --> 00:13:47.340
So again, you can define those things, but we've set most of these things up for you.

00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:52.840
And when you run that, you get this kind of intimidating object looking back at you.

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:55.979
The first two columns here were already in the tenfold object.

00:13:55.979 --> 00:13:59.619
So that's what happens when you create a RSample resampling object.

00:13:59.619 --> 00:14:03.140
But depending on the options you choose, you get at least two columns with that.

00:14:03.140 --> 00:14:05.679
One's called .metrics and one's called .notes.

00:14:05.679 --> 00:14:09.320
You can see they're list columns with a bunch of tables embedded in them.

00:14:09.320 --> 00:14:14.960
So this has all the RMSC values and R-squared values across all the ten models that we wanted

00:14:14.960 --> 00:14:16.119
to evaluate.

00:14:16.119 --> 00:14:17.760
And then that's for fold one.

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:20.539
Here's what the results would be for fold three and so on.

00:14:20.539 --> 00:14:24.719
And so what we would want to do is, if we want to get at that data and plot it and investigate

00:14:24.719 --> 00:14:30.880
it, we would want to do some, like, dplyr, tidy our unnest stuff to make that happen.

00:14:30.880 --> 00:14:33.719
Rather than putting you through that and having to write that every time, we've written a

00:14:33.719 --> 00:14:37.520
bunch of high-level accessor functions so you can just say what you want to get and

00:14:37.520 --> 00:14:41.039
not have to worry about looking up how tidy R works and things like that.

00:14:41.039 --> 00:14:45.080
So some of them, not all of them, would include things like collect my metrics.

00:14:45.080 --> 00:14:50.559
So take all these tibles that are nested and put them back into a format that I would like.

00:14:50.559 --> 00:14:54.359
And so what this does is, and let's look at the first four rows of that, is it gives you

00:14:54.359 --> 00:14:57.320
the tuning parameter values that you looked at.

00:14:57.320 --> 00:15:04.119
So for example, the first model used, the first candidate set used these four values.

00:15:04.119 --> 00:15:08.679
And its RMSE value is in log 10 units is .0796.

00:15:08.679 --> 00:15:11.679
The R squared is almost about 80%.

00:15:11.679 --> 00:15:15.840
And then we have the second set of, the second combination of tuning parameters here and

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:16.880
so on.

00:15:16.880 --> 00:15:21.159
So you might want to take these and sort them or plot them.

00:15:21.159 --> 00:15:23.640
Sometimes people just, you know, they're in a hurry or they're trying out a bunch of different

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:24.640
things.

00:15:24.640 --> 00:15:27.080
They might say, just give me the numerically best one.

00:15:27.840 --> 00:15:30.799
So let's say, give me the one with the smallest root mean squared error.

00:15:30.799 --> 00:15:35.599
And so we have functions like show best, which says, you know, for this object, give me the

00:15:35.599 --> 00:15:37.280
one with the best RMSE.

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:42.020
There's another one called select best, which actually just returns the parameter values.

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:46.239
You can select on like the three or the one standard error rule or other methods for doing

00:15:46.239 --> 00:15:47.239
that too.

00:15:47.239 --> 00:15:52.559
So there's a lot that we're not going into in a second.

00:15:52.559 --> 00:15:56.219
There's an autoplot method that I'm fairly dissatisfied with.

00:15:56.219 --> 00:15:57.979
So this can only get better.

00:15:57.979 --> 00:15:59.859
Right now it shows the marginal relationships.

00:15:59.859 --> 00:16:03.780
So if I plot the latitude degrees of freedom against let's say R squared, you can see it's

00:16:03.780 --> 00:16:05.900
like really increasing and then tanks out here.

00:16:05.900 --> 00:16:10.260
Well, the reason it tanks out here is not because it didn't want that much smoothing.

00:16:10.260 --> 00:16:14.299
It's because the penalty value associated with that particular combination was really

00:16:14.299 --> 00:16:17.099
high and that model didn't work so well.

00:16:17.099 --> 00:16:21.619
So what we need is we need a better visualization tool that could like represent what's going

00:16:21.619 --> 00:16:24.580
on here in a way that people can look at things.

00:16:24.580 --> 00:16:27.380
If you've ever seen the shiny sand package, I've always wanted to create something like

00:16:27.380 --> 00:16:28.380
that.

00:16:28.380 --> 00:16:32.580
So my thought would be, you know, if anybody wants to do that, like, you know, on the plane

00:16:32.580 --> 00:16:36.219
ride home or something, I'm not going to, you know, reject it.

00:16:36.219 --> 00:16:41.059
But an idea would be where you have your grid object and run like a shiny tune function

00:16:41.059 --> 00:16:45.940
on it and it would open up a shiny app that would let you maybe do some interactive investigation

00:16:45.940 --> 00:16:46.940
of these things.

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:47.940
So I'm hoping that's where we go.

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:49.260
It's not very hard to do.

00:16:49.260 --> 00:16:52.979
It's just a matter of like one more thing on the list of things we want to do here.

00:16:52.979 --> 00:16:54.260
So there's some autoplot methods.

00:16:54.940 --> 00:16:59.539
So let's say you want to use the numerically best results.

00:16:59.539 --> 00:17:02.500
Like just give me the one with the root mean square that's lowest.

00:17:02.500 --> 00:17:07.020
How would I weave that back into the original model objects and retrain?

00:17:07.020 --> 00:17:12.739
So what you would do is you would, let's say, select the best and that would return this

00:17:12.739 --> 00:17:13.739
table of results.

00:17:13.739 --> 00:17:16.979
We'd like a very little amount of regularization.

00:17:16.979 --> 00:17:20.459
It's about a 50-50 mixture of lasso and ridge regression.

00:17:20.459 --> 00:17:24.900
We'd like a lot of nonlinearity in the latitude and longitude data.

00:17:24.900 --> 00:17:29.180
And so, you know, so if you're fine with that, what you can do is you can splice those values

00:17:29.180 --> 00:17:32.900
back into your recipe and into your model object.

00:17:32.900 --> 00:17:37.920
And so we have these finalized functions that if you give it the recipe that has the placeholders

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:42.819
for the parameters and give it the best parameters, it just splices them back in as if you had

00:17:42.819 --> 00:17:44.020
specified them to begin with.

00:17:44.020 --> 00:17:47.540
So if you do that with the model and you print the model out, remember before it said like

00:17:47.540 --> 00:17:49.739
0.1 and 0.05.

00:17:49.739 --> 00:17:54.579
Now here are the actual values to, you know, whatever precision we have that it thinks

00:17:54.579 --> 00:17:55.579
are best.

00:17:55.579 --> 00:17:59.459
And then you can just do the regular tiny model stuff and refit this model and get to

00:17:59.459 --> 00:18:02.339
the place that you want to get to.

00:18:02.339 --> 00:18:03.660
So just some notes about that.

00:18:03.660 --> 00:18:06.660
There are these things called space-filling designs in statistics.

00:18:06.660 --> 00:18:08.500
So these work really, really well.

00:18:08.500 --> 00:18:14.020
So it's easy for us to come up with good and pretty effective default grids for you using

00:18:14.020 --> 00:18:16.180
this type of model.

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:17.619
There might be errors and warnings.

00:18:17.619 --> 00:18:22.739
And so in Carrot and a lot of other modeling functions, like across resampling, you might

00:18:22.739 --> 00:18:28.140
fit like 200 models, and maybe one of those models gives like five warnings.

00:18:28.140 --> 00:18:31.699
And so then when Carrot started running, it says, you know, you had 2,000 warnings.

00:18:31.699 --> 00:18:34.420
Type warnings to see the first 50, and you're like, huh, right?

00:18:34.420 --> 00:18:38.979
And so there's no way to trace that back to, oh, that was model 7 on resample number 3.

00:18:38.979 --> 00:18:39.979
Right?

00:18:39.979 --> 00:18:41.900
So what we do is we catch everything as we go.

00:18:42.219 --> 00:18:46.459
So if you have a model or recipe that fails, it doesn't stop anything from computing.

00:18:46.459 --> 00:18:50.739
We capture all those warnings and errors as they go, and we can associate them back to

00:18:50.739 --> 00:18:54.459
specific things where you can go back and trace and see if, like, oops, I just made

00:18:54.459 --> 00:18:56.780
a mistake or there's some weird thing in the data.

00:18:56.780 --> 00:19:02.819
So that dot notes column is a table that basically has all that information in it.

00:19:02.819 --> 00:19:07.979
The verbose mode in this, I don't have the space to show it, but I use CLI.

00:19:07.979 --> 00:19:11.540
And so I think it's kind of cool.

00:19:11.540 --> 00:19:12.619
There's a bunch of options.

00:19:12.619 --> 00:19:16.219
So if you want to save the out-of-sample predictions, you want to save the model for each folder

00:19:16.219 --> 00:19:19.339
of the recipe, you can do that and show it here.

00:19:19.339 --> 00:19:22.500
There's options for, like, all sorts of grid stuff and performance metrics.

00:19:22.500 --> 00:19:25.739
There's a lot I just sort of glossed over.

00:19:25.739 --> 00:19:30.459
Brian Lewis gave a great talk yesterday about foreach and how to use that for parallel processing.

00:19:30.459 --> 00:19:32.079
So we use that here again.

00:19:32.079 --> 00:19:35.900
So whether you're doing, like, you know, MPI or you want to do multi-core in Linux or if

00:19:35.900 --> 00:19:38.020
you're on Windows, you have to use doParallel.

00:19:38.020 --> 00:19:43.619
We have many, many options here to do parallel processing, which gives you a lot of speed

00:19:43.619 --> 00:19:44.619
ups in what you're doing.

00:19:44.619 --> 00:19:49.819
And I don't have time to talk about workflows, but workflows is another package we have where

00:19:49.819 --> 00:19:54.140
you can sort of bind together recipes and models and some other stuff together, and

00:19:54.140 --> 00:19:57.900
they're in one object, and this all works with that.

00:19:57.900 --> 00:19:58.900
So it was grid search.

00:19:58.900 --> 00:20:00.160
I have, like, a minute.

00:20:00.160 --> 00:20:04.300
So one thing that we did implement is, you know, I'm not sure if it's, like, the best

00:20:04.300 --> 00:20:08.739
choice here for the types of models, non-deep learning models we fit.

00:20:08.739 --> 00:20:12.140
But iterative search, especially during Bayesian optimization, is a big thing.

00:20:12.140 --> 00:20:14.180
It's not really that hard to implement.

00:20:14.180 --> 00:20:18.739
And so what we have is you would start off with, like, a small number of parameter values,

00:20:18.739 --> 00:20:22.020
and I can feed in the ones I just generated.

00:20:22.020 --> 00:20:26.780
And basically what Bayesian optimization does is it takes those initial 20 points, it predicts

00:20:26.780 --> 00:20:31.579
a candidate set of values, of tuning parameter values it thinks would be best to try next,

00:20:31.579 --> 00:20:36.140
and you can see after the first 10, it predicts that you should try these.

00:20:36.140 --> 00:20:37.500
It resamples them.

00:20:37.500 --> 00:20:42.500
The performance is slightly worse than the original, and it just keeps going until either

00:20:42.500 --> 00:20:46.979
you run out of iterations or it doesn't see improvement after a while.

00:20:46.979 --> 00:20:49.099
This works pretty well.

00:20:49.099 --> 00:20:51.099
Its autoplot method doesn't stink.

00:20:51.099 --> 00:20:53.660
So here's the initial set.

00:20:53.660 --> 00:20:55.180
One of them really did poorly.

00:20:55.180 --> 00:20:56.180
One of them failed.

00:20:56.180 --> 00:20:57.420
So you see a little gap here.

00:20:57.420 --> 00:21:00.819
So you can see over time or over iterations.

00:21:00.819 --> 00:21:04.060
It's staying around the current optimum that we had, and maybe if it went further, I might

00:21:04.060 --> 00:21:08.900
be able to get a big boost, but that's the results.

00:21:08.900 --> 00:21:10.979
It's almost on CRAN.

00:21:10.979 --> 00:21:14.780
It's been, like, kind of rejected, like, four times for little things.

00:21:14.780 --> 00:21:15.780
So I'm hoping.

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:16.780
Fifth time's a charm.

00:21:16.780 --> 00:21:19.699
If you want to learn more, there's a package down the site, here are the training notes

00:21:19.699 --> 00:21:24.619
from this week, and we're working on a tidy models book, so that will be in our repo probably

00:21:24.619 --> 00:21:27.859
in the next, the beginning of it, in the next few weeks.

00:21:27.859 --> 00:21:28.859
So keep an eye out for that.

00:21:28.859 --> 00:21:29.859
Thanks.

00:21:29.900 --> 00:21:30.900
Thank you.

00:21:30.900 --> 00:21:31.900
Thank you.

00:21:41.900 --> 00:21:42.900
All right.

00:21:42.900 --> 00:21:44.939
We got time for one question.

00:21:44.939 --> 00:21:49.900
Does tidy models mark the end of Carrot, or are there any plans for EG Carrot 2?

00:21:49.900 --> 00:21:53.239
I'm going to get this, like, tattooed on my arm.

00:21:53.239 --> 00:21:54.780
No, Carrot's not going anywhere.

00:21:54.780 --> 00:21:55.780
I mean, it's not.

00:21:55.780 --> 00:21:56.780
I swear to God it's not.

00:21:56.780 --> 00:21:58.780
When people ask me this question, I'm like, it's not really.

00:21:58.780 --> 00:22:01.180
I mean, it's not, like, feature complete.

00:22:01.180 --> 00:22:03.699
I'm keeping up with it and making sure everything still works.

00:22:03.699 --> 00:22:07.219
I'm putting most of our development effort into tidy models.

00:22:07.219 --> 00:22:11.300
Carrot's 15 years old, so something that's, like, 15 years old, it's hard to make a lot

00:22:11.300 --> 00:22:13.780
of big feature changes to.

00:22:13.780 --> 00:22:14.780
So it's not going away.

00:22:14.780 --> 00:22:19.900
I wouldn't expect huge, like, changes or new features in it, but it's doing pretty well

00:22:19.900 --> 00:22:20.900
as it is.

00:22:20.900 --> 00:22:21.900
So no worries there for people.

00:22:21.900 --> 00:22:22.900
All right.

00:22:22.900 --> 00:22:25.500
We'll actually do one more.

00:22:25.500 --> 00:22:29.300
What about proper support for time series forecasting in tidy models?

00:22:29.300 --> 00:22:31.140
That's a great question.

00:22:31.140 --> 00:22:33.459
So I would think we want to do that.

00:22:33.459 --> 00:22:37.859
We tend to prioritize what we implement by things either we have, like, a huge increase

00:22:37.859 --> 00:22:42.859
in interest in or things we know a lot about, and I'm not really a time series guy.

00:22:42.859 --> 00:22:47.219
We want to do this, but it's a little bit lower priority because the stuff that Rob

00:22:47.219 --> 00:22:51.619
Hyman's doing is so good that we figure, like, you're not left with nothing right now if

00:22:51.619 --> 00:22:54.319
you want to use tidyverse-type stuff with time series.

00:22:54.319 --> 00:22:59.160
So I think we'd like to use some of what he's doing there, but you already have something.

00:22:59.160 --> 00:23:03.719
So I think for the time being, unless somebody wants to implement and put in a PR or something

00:23:03.719 --> 00:23:07.599
like that, we're going to work on things that just don't exist right now before we get to

00:23:07.599 --> 00:23:08.599
those things.

00:23:08.599 --> 00:23:09.599
Thanks so much.

00:23:09.599 --> 00:23:10.599
Thank you.

